Abstract: This report is one of twenty-three country studies conducted as part of the worldwide survey of returned participants in accordance with AID/W instructions and guidelines contained in ICATO Circular A-175, November 1959.  The major purpose of this global effort was to obtain an overview of how the participant training program was progressing to ascertain ways in which future training might be more effective at the country, AID/W, and training institution levels.  The data in this study was collected and analyzed for the global study as well as to provide information useful to Peru in improving future participant training programs.  Information was gathered through 500 personal interviews with Peruvian returned participants.  In addition, 293 interviews were held with participants' current supervisors. Recommendations are implied in the report's findings, especially in the areas of training design and English language needs. (Author abstract)

Abstract: As one of nine country assessments, this study surveys Ethiopia's upper-level manpower requirements for the 1970's and how they could best met met.  The study specifically reviews available data concerning manpower needs, appraises the capabilities of indigenous Ethiopian education institutions to meet these needs, and surveys the opportunities for study overseas.  It is a relatively unstructured examination by a group of U.S. educational experts during 1964-65. Several recommendations are made in relation to overseas training. (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDES SEED CAPITAL IN CREATION OF PRIVATE COOPERATIVE DEVELOPMENT BANK (IFICOOP) WHICH WILL ADVANCE CREDIT AND FINANCE TECHNICAL/MANAGERIAL SERVICES FOR CHILEAN COOPERATIVES. IFICOOP SERVES CONSUMER, PRODUCTION (INCLUDING PROCESSINGAND MARKETING), AND SERVICE (E.G., ELECTRIC AND HOUSING) COOPERATIVES. MEMBERS OF THESE COOPS ARE ULTIMATE BENEFICIARIES OF PROJECT. IFICOOP IS ADMINISTERED BY BOARD OF DIRECTORS COMPOSED OF 13 MEMBERS ELECTED BY MEMBER COOPERATIVES. 5-MAN EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE FUNCTIONS AS PRINCIPAL MANAGEMENT BODY. IFICOOP EXTENDS LOANS WITH MAXIMUM TERM OF 10 YEARS TO COOPERATIVES WITH ADEQUATE MANAGEMENT AND FINANCIAL CAPACITY. IT PROMOTES CAPITALIZATION AND SAVING BY COOPERATIVES AND FINANCES PLANS FOR TECHNICAL AND MANAGEMENT ASSISTANCE AND TRAINIG. IT CAN GUARANTEE LOANS, CHANNEL RESOURCES OR SERVICES TO COOPS. LOANS ARE MADE FOR PHYSICAL FACILITIES, WORKING CAPITAL, OR COMMODITIES. COOPS DESIRING LOAN CAN APPLY THROUGH MAIN OFFICE OR ANY OF 5 REGIONAL OFFICES. IFICOOP MAKES INSTITUTIONAL, LEGAL, FINANCIAL ANALYSIS OF COOP. MANAGEMENT APPROVES SHORT-TERM; LOAN COMMITTEE MEDIUM OF LONG-TERM UP TO CERTAIN LIMIT; EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE APPROVES LONG-TERM EXCEEDING LIMIT. READJUSTMENT INDEXES ARE APPLIED TO LOANS TO AVOID DECAPITALIZATION DUE TO INFLATION. US ADVISOR GUIDES OVERALL POLICY, ASSISTS WITH OPERATING PROCEDURES. USAID LOAN FUNDSPROVIDE ASSISTANCE IN PROJECT PLANNING FROM PRIVATE FIRMS, CAPITAL FOR COOPERATIVE RELENDING, REGIONAL OFFICES, US EXPERT. BANCO DEL ESTADO, CORFO, COOPERATIVE MEMBERS PROVIDE ADDITIONAL CAPITAL.

Abstract: LOAN & DOLLAR GRANT TO THE GOVT OF ECUADOR TO UPGRADE PRIMARY LEVEL EDUCATION. THIS ACTIVITY IS A SUBPROJECT OF ECUADOR-PRIMARY EDUC IMPROVEMENT PROJECT AND PROVIDES APPROX 1/2 THE FUNDING NEEDED TO CONSTRUCT NEW PRIMARY & SECONDARY LEVEL SCHOOL FACILITIES IN 20 PROVINCES AND TEACHER HOUSING IN REMOTE AREAS. SPECIFIC PROJECT COMPONENTS INCLUDE CONSTRUCTING: 1)609 SCHOOLS WITH 3000 CLASSROOMS TO PRIVATE NEW FACILITIES FOR 120000 PRIMARY AGE CHILDREN; 2)ONE NEW NORMAL (SECONDARY) SCHOOL AT GUAYAQUIL & ADDITIONAL OR REPLACEMENT FACILITIES AT THE UYUMBICHO NORMAL SCHOOL NEAR QUITO (800 STUDENT CAPACITY EACH)-THESE NORMAL SCHOOLS TO BE UTILIZED IN A TEACHER-TRAINING SUB-PROJECT; 3)THIRTY TEACHERS LODGINGS IN REMOTE AREAS TO ATTRACT TEACHERS TO THESE AREAS; 4)ONE DEMONSTRATIONAL PRIMARY SCHOOL USED IN CONNECTION WITH THE NORMAL SCHOOLS. THIS BUILDING PROJECT IS ADMINISTERED BY THE GOL MOE COOPERATIVE PROGRAM FOR SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION(CPSC)ORGANIZATION WHICH ALSO PROVIDES THE BUILDING DESIGNS(WITH ASSISTANCE FROM THE USAID & PEACE CORPS), AND PROCURES ALL CONSTRUCTION EQUIPMENT, MATERIALS & SUPPLIES FROM LOCAL & US SOURCES. SUPERVISING THE CONSTRUCTION IS A CONTRACTED US ARCHITECTURAL-ENGINEERING FIRM COORDINATING THE EFFORTS OF THIS SUB-PROJECT WITH OTHERS UNDER THE MAIN PROJECT ARE AN EDUC GENERALIST RECRUITED BY AID. LOCAL BUILDING CONTRACTORS USED WHEN POSSIBLE ALONG WITH LOCAL MATERIALS AND LABOR.

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDED TO THE GOVERNMENT OF TURKEY TO ASSIST IN FINANCING THE DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION OF A DAM AND HYDROELECTRIC POWER PLANT AT KEBAN ON THE EUPHRATES (FIRAT) RIVER IN EAST-CENTRAL TURKEY AS WELL AS RELATED SUBSTATIONS AND TRANSMISSION LINES. THE KEBAN DAM WILL BE OF ROLLED ROCK-FILL CONSTRUCTION, RISING 510 FEET ABOVE RIVER BOTTOM, AND TWO-THIRDS OF A MILE IN LENGTH. FOUR 155 MW TURBOGENERATOR UNITS WILL BE INSTALLED, WITH PROVISION FOR FOUR MORE UNITS IN THE FUTURE, YIELDING A TOTAL CAPACITY OF 1,240,000 MW. THE TRANSMISSION FACILITIES WILL CONSIST OF TWO EXTRA-HIGH VOLTAGE (380 KV) "BACK-BONE" TRANSMISSION LINES TRAVERSING TWO-THIRDS THE LENGTH OF TURKEY TO ISTANBUL AND ABOUT 300 MILES OF SINGLE CIRCUIT 154 KV LINES SERVING AREAS EAST AND SOUTH OF KEBAN. IN ADDITION TO THE CONSTRUCTION AND EQUIPMENT CONTRACTS FOR THE PROJECT PROPER, MANY SUPPLEMENTARY ACTIVITIES WILL BE REQUIRED. THESE WILL INCLUDE: ACCESS ROADS TO THE SITE; CONSTRUCTION POWER; RAIL, ROAD, AND HARBOR FACILITIES FOR MOVING PROJECT EQUIPMENT AND MATERIAL; LAND ACQUISITION AND RESETTLEMENT; AND RELOCATION OF ROADS, RAILROADS, AND COMMUNICATIONS IN THE RESERVOIR AREA. THE STATE HYDRAULIC WORKS (DSI), A GENERAL DIRECTORATE UNDER THE MINISTRY OF ENERGY AND NATURAL RESOURCES, WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR CONSTRUCTION OF THE DAM AND POWER PLANT. DSI WILL ALSO OWN AND OPERATE THE FACILITY AFTER CONSTRUCTION. ETIBANK, A STATE OWNED INDUSTRIAL BANK, WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE CONSTRUCTION OF THE TRANSMISSION LINES AS WELL AS THEIR OWNERSHIP AND OPERATION. OTHER LENDERS TO THE PROJECT INCLUDE: GERMANY, FRANCE, ITALY, EUROPEAN INVESTMENT BANK, AND THE INTERNATIONAL DEVELOPMENT ASSOCIATION. THE RELIABILITY AND LOW COST OF POWER FROM KEBAN WILL STIMULATE INDUSTRIAL EXPANSION IN TURKEY.

Abstract: UGANDA PROVIDED WITH TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND COMMODITIES TO IMPROVE ADMINISTRATIVE AND MANAGEMENT SKILLS OF CIVIL SERVANTS BY UPGRADING IN-SERVICE TRAINING AT UGANDA'S INSTITUTE OF PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION (U-IPA). PROJECT STRESSED TRAINING RELEVANT TO UGNADA'S NATIONAL AND ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT. MANAGEMENT TRAINING OFFERED OVER BROAD SPECTRUM WITH AGRICULTURE, LOCAL ADMINSTRATION AND LAW ENFORCEMENT EMPHASIZED. PROJECT DIRECTED AT ADMINISTRATIVE, EXECUTIVE, AND LOCAL GOVERNMENT LEVELS. TRAINING VARIED FROM HIGH POWERED SEMINARS AND CONFERENCES LASTING ONLY SEVERAL DAYS TO ESTABLISHMENT OF 9-MONTH DIPLOMA COURSES IN PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION AND BUSINESS MANAGEMENT. COURSE CONTENT EMPHASIZED PROJECT DESIGN AND IMPLEMENTATION WITH INSTRUCTION IN SUCH MODERN TECHNIQUES AS CHARTING, CRITICAL PATHS, COST-BENEFIT ANALYSIS, AND COST ACCOUNTING. MANAGEMENT TRAINING MANUALS, CASE STUDIES, AND SYLLABUS MATERIAL DEVELOPED. INSTRUCTION SUPPLEMENTED WITH CONSULTATIONS ON SPECIFIC PROBLEMS IN GOVERNMENT AGENCIES. U/IPA RESEARCH PROGRAM STRENGTHENED AND WORKING RELATIONSHIP ESTABLISHED WITH MAKERS UNIVERSITY. MARCH 1972 PAR NOTED DELAY IN PROCUREMENT AND DELIVERY OF BOOKS AND MATERIALS FOR PLANNED LIBRARY EXPANSION. U.S. PARTICIPANT TRAINING PROVIDED FOR U/IPA COUNTERPARTS. UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN AND INSTITUTE OF PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION-NEW YORK CONTRACTED FOR TECHNICAL ADVISORY ASSISTANCE. OTHER DONERS INCLUDED UNITED KINGDOM AND COMMONWEALTH SECRETARIAT, CONTRIBUTING BASIC STAFF. UNDP ALSO SPONSORED CORRESPONDENCE AND TRAINING PROGRAMS FOR LOCAL AUTHORITIES. ROCKEFELLER FOUNDATION CONTRIBUTED TO DEVELOPMENT OF U/IPA-MAKERE UNIVERSITY JOINT PROGRAMS. DANISH GOVERNMENT PROVIDED LOAN FOR PHYSICAL PLANT TO ACCOMODATE DIPLOMA COURSE IN BUSINESS MANAGEMENT.

Abstract: This report assesses how well this particular program was operating and suggests improvements in future efforts. Many specific recommendations are contained in the report in the areas of training design, selection of participants, support services, follow-up, utilization of training, and professional development. Abstract: Evaluates project to improve the Government of Paraguay's (GOP) tax administration.  This collection of 15 monthly progress reports by the Internal Revenue Service technicians covers the period 4/1/65-10/31/73, with many monthly gaps.  No methodology is indicated. Various measures were suggested to the Ministry of Finance to improve tax collection, enforcement, and administration in the Office of Income Tax (OIT), the Real Property Tax Office (PTO), and the Internal Tax Office (ITO).  Plans for decentralizing the tax collection and taxpayer education and appeal functions of each of these offices were suggested, approved, and implemented.  As a result of in-country training programs, organization and methods (O&M) groups were established in each office. Recommendations for updating and maintaining taxpayer and property files and other records were made and implemented.  The O&M groups were assisted in designing organizational charts for their respective offices and in consolidating all effective rulings and regulations.  New audit forms and procedures were developed and implemented, increasing greatly the effectiveness of these functions across the board. Field collectors were recruited and trained to help reduce the number of delinquent accounts. This effort was aided by the in-country training of field auditors. The major, persisting, problem encountered by the IRS advisors during this period was the failure to install a centralized planning function within the Ministry of Finance which would coordinate the activities, training, program planning, etc., of these and other tax offices.

Abstract: Reports on the progress of the construction contractor, Smith Hinchman & Grylls Associates, Inc. in a project to establish a medical and dental sciences education center in Vietnam.  Two reports are contained within this document. During the reporting period 1/1/65 to 7/l/65, the contractor's work was interrupted on several occasions due to late arrival of import commodities.  The resident architect and the ministry of education and culture tentatively agreed to a five-month extension requested by the contractor because of these import delays and because of delays caused by civil disturbances.  The official two-year construction period for the basic sciences buildings began 5/l/63.  The contractor, whose responsibilities were primarily technical and supervisory, has maintained excellent relations with local workers and the GVN.  The resident architect-engineer requested permission to terminate his position.  All major architectural items have been completed. During the period 7/1/65 to 1/1/66, the contractor was unable to keep on schedule.  Work performance in the installation of electrical and mechanical equipment was below average. The contractor appears unable to obtain trained personnel qualified and capable of meeting deadlines. Also orienting local technicians to American equipment and systems taxed the project director to the utmost during this project period.  A third construction extension to 3/17/66 has been requested.  The contractor's leadership was competent and excellent relations were maintained with USAID and the host country.

Abstract: Evaluates one component of the Agricultural Services project in Somalia for the period 1/62 - 12/64.  The component evaluated is the National Agricultural Research Station being established near Afgoi which will consolidate major agricultural experimentation efforts into one area. A good deal of initial planning and development work has been done. Land has been cleared and prepared for farming, equipment and supplies procured, a reasonably well-trained staff is available, and funding has been arranged. Some trials of sorghum and rice have been conducted. The project is, however, 12 to 18 months behind schedule.  Failure of the host government to grant to the Ministry of Agriculture title to the land and legal rights to irrigation water from the river was the chief factor hampering early progress of the project.  Once title to land and water were granted in mid-1964, studies of the land water, irrigation, and planning of the station moved rapidly. Additional implementation delays are caused by the long time required to procure supplies and equipment, particularly spare parts. The author also points out that the Somali cultural background is not particularly conductive to the rapid building of agricultural research stations.  Traditionally, the average Somali is a member of an elaborate tribal social order, is not work-oriented, and is interested in the relative (and somewhat false) security of owning large numbers of livestock.  With few academically trained agriculturalists in the country, the average Somali has little or no concept of what such an institution can mean to him or his country. The Somoli government has not provided any counterparts to work with USAID technicians. Consequently, Ministry of Agriculture personnel do not always have a sound understanding of technical factors or objectives involved. One phase of the station has developed faster than expected:  The Soils Laboratory is well organized, fairly well equipped, and has been serving the country for nearly two years. A contract has been signed with the University of Wyoming to take over development and operation of the project.

Abstract: EVALUATES PROJ PERFORMANCE AS OF 10/65 IN MOROCCO.  PURPOSE OF PROJ WAS TO BRING ABOUT THE IRRIGATION OF APPROX 176000 ACRES OF FARMLAND AND THE INTRODUCTION OF SOUND IRRIG FARMING PRACTICES IN THE TARGET AREA. US DEPT OF AGR/US DEPT OF INT ERIOR STUDY TEAM OBTAINED THE INFORMATION FOR THIS EVAL THROUGH INTERVIEWS WITH GOM, USAID, US EMBASSY, UN, AND HYDROTECHNIC CORP OFFICIALS;ON-SITE OBSERV AT TARGET AREA FARMS;AND DISCUSSIONS WITH FARMERS AND THE STAFF MEMBERS OF THE EXPERIMENT STATIONS, LIVESTOCK BREEDING STATIONS, PROCESSING PLANTS & THE PERIMETER (PROJ AREA) HEADQUARTERS OF BOTH THE TADLA AND LOWER MOULOUYA PROJS. ALTHOUGH AT TIME OF EVAL ONLY 32000 ACRES HAD BEEN BROUGHT UNDER IRRIG,THE FUTURE OF THE PROJ,GIVEN ADEQUATE FUNDING,APPEARED FAVORABLE.IT WAS DETERMND THAT: THE GOM PLACES A HIGH PRIORITY ON THE ACHIEVEMENT OF PROJ GOALS; GOM PLANS FOR THE DEVEL OF THIS PROJ ARE FEASIBLE & EFFECTIVE; COMPLETED CONSTRUCTION FOR THE PROJ IS OF HIGH QUALITY; THERE ARE SUFFICIENT WATER RESOURCES FOR THE TARGET AREA AND THE SOIL QUALITY OF AREA IS GENERALLY GOOD; UPPER-LVL GOMPERSNNL ASSIGNED TO PROJ ARE WELL-QUALIFIED; AND THE TARGET FARMERS ARE PERHAPS THE BEST IN MOROCCO. THERE DID APPEAR TO BE A SHORTAGE OF QUALIFIED GOM PERSNNL AT THE PERIMETER LEVEL;GOM HAS RESPONDED TO THIS THROUGH PERSNNL CHANGES. IT IS RECOMMENDED: 1)FEAS STUDIES OF THE TRIFFA & GAREB PLAIN BE POSTPONED UNTIL MORE IS KNOWN OF THE WATER SUPPLY IN THOSE AREAS; 2)STUDY SHOULD BE CNDUCTED TO DETERMINE HOW TO PROTEC T THE MECHRA KLILA RESERVOIR FROM FILLING WITH SEDIMENT; 3)ANNUAL COMMITMENTS FROM THE NEW LOAN (TO COMPLETE PROJ)SHOULD BE DETERMINED BY PROGRESS ACHIEVED BY GOM IN MEETING PROJ SCHEDULE; 4)MANPOWER SURVEY SHOULD BE CONDUCTED OF THE AVAILABILITY & NEEDS OF AGR TECHS DURING THE NEXT 5 YRS; 5)SUBSTANTIVE IN-SRVC TRNG PROGS BE IMPLEMENTED FOR GOM PROJ PERSNNL; 6)US TECHS SHOULD BE USED AS CONSULTANTS; NUMBER OF FOREIGN TECHS IN OPER POSITIONS BE HELD TO A MINIMUM; 7)UNIRRIG PROJ AREA GRASSLANDS SHOULD BE SEEDED & HAVE CONTROLLED GRAZING; 8)BRANCH OF ECON & STATS BE ESTBLSHD AT HQ'S LAND DEVEL DIV; 9)MODEL CMV BE ESTBLSHD IN LOWER MOUL AREA.

Abstract: This report presents the proceedings of a two-phase seminar-workshop held in 1965 on the extra-curricular aspects of A.I.D.'s participant training program.  The workshop, attended by social scientists and A.I.D. personnel, addressed and provided recommendations for improving the areas of trainee selection, program planning, orientation and counseling, integration of trainees in U.S. culture, and follow up on returned trainees. Areas for further research are specified.  (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: Project to finance the installation of two 1500 KW diesel electric generators at Kandahar in Afghanistan until power from the long-range Kajakai project becomes available.  The implementing agency will be the Kandahar Electric Company (KEC) a branch of the state-controlled Afghan Electric Company (AEC). Consulting services for the purchase and installation of the two generators will be provided by an American engineering firm, which will subsequently provide approximately 6 man-years of services for supervision of operation and maintenance of the plant and the training of Afghan personnel.  The generators will be medium-sized (under 1,000 RPM), with a frequency of 50 cycles and a base load for at least 5 years, and will generate approximately 3,300 volts.  More precise specifications will be determined by the consulting engineer.  The generators will be located adjacent to the New Diesel Plant and will be capable of being moved to another location in Afghanistan when no longer needed after completion of the planned long-range permanent power source at Kajakai Dam, projected for 1971.

Abstract: Grant to Sao Paulo Light S.A. to construct transmission and distribution facilities to improve and expand its electrical power system in Sao Paulo, Brazil.  Project funds will be used to:  (1) construct a new or reinforce an existing tunnel at the Henry Borden plant and procure replacement parts, spare runners, and windings; (2) construct and rebuild circuits, overhead lines, and underground cables; (3) increase the capacity of substations; (4) add lines and transformers; and (5) provide work equipment, meters, personnel training, and special studies.

Abstract: A French/English and English/French glossary of terms currently used by soil scientists is presented for use by students specializing in agronomy and soil science and by translators of specialized documents. Certain elementary terms have been incorporated for use by students not well versed in English or French.  Gender is indicated in the French part of the glossaries, and the feminine form of adjectives is provided when different from the masculine. The glossaries are followed by a list of 200 English verbs and 200 French verbs frequently used in soil science.

Abstract: 6/2/65-12/30/65. CONTRACTOR CLEARLY UNDERSTANDS THE SCOPE AND NATURE OF CONTRACT OBJECTIVES. CONTRACTOR HAS PROGRESSED TOWARD OBTAINING OBJECTIVES. MINISTRY OF AGRICULTURE IS PROVIDING FUNDS INDICATED IN PROAG. THE QUALITY OF RESEARCH IS OUTSTANDING AND ON-THE-JOB TRAINING OF RESEARCH PERSONNEL IS GOOD. CONTRACT REPRESENTATIVE VISITED THE EXPERIMENTAL STATIONS AND AREAS WHERE RESEARCH PROJECTS HAVE BEEN DEVELOPED AND FOUND WORK TO BE PROGRESSING WELL. PERSONNEL UNDER CONTRACT ARE WELL QUALIFIED FOR THEIR JOBS BUT SOME OF THE MOST HIGHLY QUALIFIED SCIENTISTS ARE ON SABBATICAL LEAVE SO THEY ARE ONLY AVAILABLE FOR ONE YEAR. PLANS ARE TO HIRE PEACE CORPS VOLUNTEERS COMPLETING THEIR ASSIGNMENTS TO TRAIN UNDER THESE SCIENTISTS. CONTRACTOR WORKS SATISFACTORILY WITH LOCAL WORKERS AND ALSO COOPERATES WELL WITH USAID PERSONNEL AND OTHER CONTRACTORS. CONTRACTOR HAS NOT SENT ANY PARTICIPANTS TO FOREIGN COUNTRIES FOR FORMAL TRAINING IN RESEARCH METHODS OR ADMINISTRATION DUE TO ENGLISH LANGUAGE REQUIREMENT. COOPERATION OF THE MINISTRY OF AGRICULTURE HAS BEEN VERY GOOD DURING THE PAST 6 MONTHS BUT THERE HAS BEEN A DELAY IN THE NEGOTIATIONS BETWEEN USAID AND THE GOB ON RELEASE OF T.C. FUNDS. CONTRACTOR HAS OBTAINED A MONTHS SUPPY OF CRUZEIROS FROM P.L. 480 MONEY BUT IS DELFYING IMPLEMENTATION OF NEW PROJECTS BECAUSE OF UNCERTAINTY ON FORTHCOMING FUND. THERE HAS BEEN SOME DIFFICULTY IN RECRUITING LONG-TERM PERSONNEL. CONSEQUENTLY THERE ARE ONLY 29 AS OPPOSED TO EXPECTED TOTAL OF 35 TECHNICIANS.

Abstract: Evaluates project performance from 3/30/62 to 6/30/65 in Peru. Program assists Govt of Peru (GOP) to increase knowledge, skills & capabilities of its populatn through the establishmt of a total educatnal program.  Evaluatn methodology not defined. A great deal has been accomplished in GOP's attempt to upgrade educatnal skills.  Columbia Univ (CU) has provided Peru's Ministry of Educatn (MOE) with educatnal planning assist, inservice & pre-service teacher training, curriculum & teaching materials for the Developmt Center, technical and/or educational services, constructn & equipmt acquisitn, and overseas training for 32 Peruvian educators.  With CU assistance, MOE worked out plans to improve educational programs through primary, secondary, technical, and industrial educational systems; community devel; educational admin; scholarship programs; and educational evaluatn. Team members have visited all types of schools, analyzed instructn methods & materials, and studied building constructn.  Team has also engaged in orientatn activities; assisted MOE develop its 5 year educational plan & organize a scholarship program; and conducted training sessions for educators.  USAID has exhibited understanding of Peru's educatnal difficulties & offered MOE timely suggestns. Despite progress, improvemt is slow, since Peru's literacy rate at program's inceptn was only 50%; skilled & semi skilled personnel were lacking.  The frequent changes in administrative personnel, poor laws or failure to implemt useful laws on the books & insufficient funds are a constant obstacle.  Other probs have been CU team member's inability to communicate in Spanish and quickly assess cultural & governmental motivatns. Evaluator feels Peru's educational solutn depends on its ability to provide adequate technical assistance, and persuade its private sector to provide funds & training.  Since MOE's requests are too extensive to be accomplished by a staff of 10 technicians, these needs should be realisticly revised according to major priorities.

Abstract: As one of nine country studies, this report surveys Tunisia's upper-level manpower requirements for the 1970's and how they could best be met.  The analysis reviews available data on high-level manpower needs, appraises the capabilities of indigenous education institutions to meet these needs, and surveys the opportunities for study overseas. It is a relatively unstructured examination by a group of U.S. educational experts during 1964-65.  Several recommendations are made on overseas study in general.  (Author abstract)

Abstract: As one of nine country studies, this report surveys Nigeria's upper-level manpower requirements for the 1970's and how they could best be met.  The analysis includes a review of available data concerning high-level manpower needs, appraises the capabilities of indigenous education institutions to meet these needs, and surveys opportunities for overseas training. Abstract: As one of the nine country studies, this report surveys Kenya, Uganda, and Tanzania's upper-level manpower requirements for the 1970's and how they could best be met.  The analysis includes a review of available data on high-level manpower needs, appraises the capabilities of indigenous education institutions in each country to meet these needs, and surveys the opportunities for study overseas.  It is a relatively unstructured examination by a group of U.S. educational experts between 1964-65.  Several recommendations are made on overseas training opportunities. (Author abstract)

Abstract: This report, one of 23 country studies conducted as part of a wordlwide survey, reviews A.I.D.'s participant training program in British Honduras (now Belize) from 1953 to 1963.  The report was based on interviews with 78 of 98 returned participants, as well as with 39 supervisors and two U.S. technicians. Recommendations address the areas of training design, pre-departure preparation, support services, follow-up, and the utilization of training.  (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: A summary report of nine country studies (Ethiopia, Guinea, Kenya, Liberia, Nigeria, Sudan, Tanzania, Tunisia, Uganda) on manpower requirements for the 1970's and how they could best be met, this study focuses principally upon high-level manpower demand and supply.  The educational capabilities of these countries to meet manpower needs is assessed, the level of overseas study by African students measured, and the extent to which participants will meet known educational needs examined; the study also identifies bottlenecks and imbalances in educational development and suggests areas in which external assistance can be best employed.  (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: REPORTS ON THE PROGRESS OF THE CONSTRUCTION CONTRACTOR,SMITH HINCHMAN & GRYLLS ASSOCIATES,INC IN A PROJECT TO ESTABLISH A MEDICAL AND DENTAL SCIENCES EDUCATION CENTER IN VIETNAM. REPORT NUMBER 28 DETAILS ACTIVITIES UNDERTAKEN DURING 12/64 IN THE CONSTRUCTION OF THE CENTER'S FOUR PRINCIPAL BUILDINGS AS WELL AS A UTILITY BUILDING, RESIDENCE AND GATEHOUSE. DEMOLITION,BUILDING EXCAVATION,CONCRETE FOUNDATION,FRAMING,FILLING AND BACKFILLING WERE ESTIMATED TO BE 100% COMPLETE. REPORT NUMBER 30 COVERS 2/65. ONE WEEK OF WORK WAS LOST DUE TO TET HOLIDAYS. ALSO,COMPLETION BY THE SCHEDULED DATE APPEARED UNLIKELY DUE TO THE LATE ARRIVAL OF BUILD-IN COMMODITIES FURNISHED BY THE US GOVT AND DIFFICULTIES ENCOUNTERED BY THE CONTRACTOR IN IMPORTING JAPANESE FINISH TILE. SINCE THE START OF WORK ON 3/20/63, 106,035 MAN-DAYS OF LABOR HAVE BEEN EXPENDED (EXCLUSIVE OF FIELD STAFF). FEBRUARY ACCOUNTED 6094 MAN-DAYS. TWO MONTHS OF CONSTRUCTION TIME REMAIN. THE CONTRACTOR APPEARS UNABLE TO OBTAIN TRAINED PERSONNEL QUALIFIED AND CAPABLE OF MEETING DEADLINES. ALSO ORIENTING LOCAL TECHNICIANS TO AMERICAN EQUIPMENT AND SYSTEMS TAXED THE PROJECT DIRECTOR TO THE UTMOST DURING THIS PROJECT PERIOD. A THIRD CONSTRUCTION EXTENSION TO 3/17/66 HAS BEEN REQUESTED. THE CONTRACTOR'S LEADERSHIP WAS COMPETENT AND EXCELLENT RELATIONS WERE MAINTAINED WITH USAID AND THE HOST-COUNTRY.

Abstract: AS OF 12/31/64. THE CONTRACTOR, THE UNIVERSITY OF PITTSBURGH, HAS DONE A FIRST-RATE JOB IN EVERY RESPECT. THE INSTITUTE OF ADMINISTRATION AT ZARIA HAS BEEN INCORPORATED INTO AHMADU BELLO UNIVERSITY. THE INSTITUTE'S PROGRAM HAS BEEN STEADILY UPGRADED THROUGH THE SUCCESSFUL INTRODUCTION OF A TWO-YEAR DIPLOMA COURSE, WHICH IS NOW EXTENDED TO A THREE-YEAR BACCALAUREATE PROGRAM FOR QUALIFYING STUDENTS. THE CURRICULUM HAS BEEN STRENGTHENED BY THE ADDITION OF COURSES IN ACCOUNTING, ENTERPRISE MANAGEMENT AND INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS. NEW TEACHING TECHNIQUES, SUCH AS CASE STUDIES, WORK SHOPS, AND STUDENT RESEARCH PROJECTS, HAVE BEEN INTRODUCED. AN ACTIVE PUBLICATIONS PROGRAM INCLUDES THE PREPARATION OF TEXTBOOKS, MANUALS, AND CONFERENCE PROCEEDINGS. THE LIBRARY HAS BEEN BUILT (WITH USAID FUNDS) AND THE VOLUME OF BOOKS AND PERIODICALS AS WELL AS STUDENT UTILIZATION IS GROWING RAPIDLY. THE CONFERENCE PROGRAM, UNDER THE DIRECTION OF A PITTSBURGH SPECIALIST, IS MOST SUCCESSFUL. IT PROVIDES RESEARCH AND CASE STUDY MATERIAL AS WELL AS A FORUM FOR EXCHANGE OF IDEAS ON SUCH PROBLEMS AS URBANIZATION, CENTRAL SERVICES TO LOCAL GOVERNMENT, AND THE CONTRIBUTION OF LOCAL GOVERNMENT TO ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT. THE INSTITUTE CONDUCTS A WIDE VARIETY OF SHORT-TERM IN-SERVICE TRAINING PROGRAMS FOR PUBLIC SERVICE PERSONNEL AT ALL LEVELS, WITH THE ACTIVE DIRECTION/PARTICIPATION OF PITTSBURGH PERSONNEL.

Abstract: EVALUATES PERFORMANCE OF ALFRED L FOUST ON A RURAL ELECTRIFICATION PROJECT IN BOLIVIA FROM 7/3/64 TO 1/1/65. CONTRACTOR WAS TO PROVIDE ENGINEERING ADVISORY SERVICES TO THE NATIONAL ROADS SERVICE FOR CONSTRUCTION OF THE ALCOCHE-TIPUANI GOLD ROAD, CONSTRUCTION OF THE AVISPAS-MINAS MAYU ROAD, AND ROAD REHABILITATION IN THE OKINAWAN COLONIES. MR FOUST'S DISCUSS ONS AND REPORTS INDICATE THAT HE HAS A CLEAR UNDERSTANDING OF THE SCOPE AND NATURE OF THE CONTRACT OBJECTIVES. 30 KILOMETERS OF THE GOLD ROAD HAVE BEEN SURVEYED; 15 KM DESIGNED, AND A CONTRACT HAS BEEN SIGNED FOR THE CONSTRUCTION OF THE ENTIRE PROJECT. 5 KM OF THE AVISPAS-MINAS MAYU ROAD HAVE BEEN CONSTRUCTED, AND DESIGN PLANS HAVE BEEN COMPLETED FOR AN ADD TIONAL 5KM. PLANS FOR A PORTION OF THE OKINAWAN COLONY ROADS HAVE BEEN COMPLETED, AND SELF-HELP ROAD CONSTRUCTION WILL START THIS MONTH. PRELIMINARY STUDIES AND PLANS ARE UNDERWAY ON A LONG RANGE OBJECTIVE OF THIS CONTRACT -- THE ALL WEATHER STABILIZATION OF ALL ROADS IN BOLIVIA, BY THE USE OF SALT, LIME, MINERAL AGGREGATE ASPHALT, OR SOIL CEMENT. PRIMARY HINDRANCE IS THE LACK OF FUNDS FOR CARRYING OUT THE OBJECTIVES. MEASURES ARE BEING TAKEN TO FACILITATE THE REMOVAL OF THIS OBSTACLE..

Abstract: PRESENTS A COLLECTION OF TWELVE ESSAYS WHICH WERE PREPARED FOR A SERIES OF SEMINARS AT HARVARD UNIVERSITY ON THE THEORY AND PRACTICE OF TRANSPORT INVESTMENT PLANNING IN DEVELOPING COUNTRIES. THE EMERGING NATIONS OF ASIA, AFRICA, AND LATIN AMERICA NEED GUIDELINES FOR DESIGNING MORE EFFICIENT TRANSPORT SYSTEMS. POLICYMAKERS RECOGNIZE THE IMPORTANCE OF TRANSPORT AS AN INSTRUMENT OF ECONOMIC PROGRESS, BUT THEY LACK THE SUBSTANTIVE BACKGROUND FOR MAKING INVESTMENT DECISIONS THAT WILL SERVE ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT WITHOUT ALLOCATING TOO LARGE OR TOO SMALL A SHARE OF NATIONAL INCOME TO THE TRANSPORT SECTOR. THE ESSAYS IN THIS BOOK PROVIDE NEW THEORETICAL INSIGHTS AND ANALYSES OF EXPERIENCE THAT SHOULD BE USEFUL IN SUCH PLANNING. THE ESSAYS DEAL WITH TRANSPORT SYSTEM OBJECTIVES, TECHNOLOGY, DESIGN, REGIONAL AND NATIONAL SHORT-TERM AND LONG-TERM PLANNING, FINANCING OF INVESTMENT, AND OTHER ISSUES. CASE STUDIES OF PLANNING IN THE SOVIET UNION AND CHILE ARE ALSO PRESENTED.

Abstract: This report evaluates the 1965 Summer Leadership Programs for A.I.D. participants through a combination of interviews, observation, and informal discussions.  Although no longer a part of A.I.D.'s training program, the purpose of the Summer Leadership program was to diversify students experience in the United States, giving them insights into U.S. cultural life and academic assistance.  Each program offered lectures and seminars on leadership and arrange "enrichment program" homestays, travel, field trips, and internships for participants.  Very few recommendations of value to A.I.D. emerged from the report. (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: This staff report assesses the operations of the Office of International Training (OIT) in relation to participant arrival, in-training support and monitoring, and participant departure. Phase I traces the PIO/P from the mission to AID/W, while Phase II analyzes the implementation of the program.  The report makes recommendations for improving OIT's operations and its coordination with other participating agencies.  Recommendations relate to OIT/IT's office management and its participant reporting system.  (Participant training abstract, modified)

Abstract: This RAND Memorandum suggests several areas in which, through bargaining, AID might profitably persuade India to improve its economic policies.  The incentives available to AID are variations in the amount of U.S. assistance given to India.  The areas chosen are those where existing Indian policy appears to create serious and unnecessary impediments to economic development.  Specifically, the Memorandum singles out the Indian government's price and allocation policies for foreign exchange and for a number of particularly scarce industrial and consumer goods. The Memorandum begins by looking at AID's brief and only partly successful experience with macro-bargaining in India.  Then it suggests a number of general considerations for selecting bargaining areas and bargaining instruments.  In particular, the Memorandum suggests that the 1964 bargaining may not have offered sufficient incentives to India, that negative incentives (penalties) may be more effective in securing compliance, and that in the case of India a few specific policy changes are likely to be more effective criteria of achievement than aggregate measures of economic performance. With respect to India's policy on foreign exchange, or, more generally, the balance of payments, the Memorandum suggests that the United States provide incentives for (1) an effective devaluation of the rupee (either by direct devaluation or other means), (2) changes in other government policies inimical to exports, and (3) replacement of the present system of administrative import controls by the price mechanism and various appropriate fiscal means.  Various alternatives to devaluation itself are examined, with the conclusion that exchange auctions offer some net advantages. The Memorandum then examines Indian domestic price and allocation policies, and contends that substantial returns are likely from incentives that encourage India to replace direct controls as a means of allocating particularly scarce commodities.  Four alternatives to the present administrative allocation system are considered.  The most attractive of these involves a greater reliance on the market mechanism, with government control exercised through excise taxes. Finally, some general comments are made about the role AID might play in encouraging the Government of India to make desired policy changes. Several advantages are seen in working through the aid-giving Consortium and in coordination with the World Bank.  Particular attention is directed to the problem of overcoming the opposition of the Indian Administrative Services to a relaxation of direct controls.  (Author abstract)

Abstract: This report is one of twenty-three country studies conducted as part of the worldwide survey of returned participants in accordance with AID/W instructions and guidelines contained in ICATO Circular A-175, November 1959.  The major purpose of this global effort was to obtain an overview of how the participant training program was progressing to ascertain ways in which future training might be more effective at the country, AID/W, and training institution levels.  The study involved 249 Jordanian participants who were interviewed along with 25 supervisors and 13 U.S. technicians.  Many specific recommendations are made on training design, location of training and pre-departure preparation, English language, orientation, support services, follow-up, and utilization of training. (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: EVALUATES PROJECT TO ASSIST THE GOVERNMENT OF LIBERIA (GOL) DEVELOP A PROFESSIONAL AND HIGHER EDUCATIONAL SYSTEM AT THE UNIVERSITY OF LIBERIA (UL) FROM 6/64 TO 12/64. CONTRACTOR /(CORNELL UNIV) HAS A CLEAR UNDERSTANDING OF THE SCOPE AND NATURE OF CONTRACT OBJECTIVES AND HAS SUBMITTED ALLL REQUESTED INFORMATION TO THE GOL IN A TIMELY MANNER. ATTEMPTS ARE BEING MADE TO STRENGHTEN THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN UL AND CORNELL UNIV (CU) AND TO MODIFY THE STAFFING PATTERN. UL HAS MADE GREATER PROGRESS IN THE PAST 2 YEARS THAN IN ANY PREVIOUS DECADE DUE TO THE EXCELLENT ASSISTANCE OF CU AND LEADERSHIP OF UL'S CHIEF OF PARTY. UL'S PARTICIPANT TRAINING PROGRAM AND ON-THE-JOB TRAINING CONDUCTED BY CU TEAM IS PREPARING LIBERIAN STAFF AND FACULTY TO REPLACE CU MEMBERS AND TO IMPROVE UL ADMINISTRATION PRACTICES. SU IS IN TURN BEING INCLUDED IN MORE DECISION MAKING ACTIVITIES. GOOD EXAMPLES SET BY THE EUROPEAN AND AMERICAN FACULTY AND STAFF MEMBERS (50% OF UL STAFF) ARE INFLUENCING THE LIBERIAN UL PERSONNEL TO SHOW MORE INITIATIVE AND FOLLOW BETTER WORK HABITS. UL FUNDING HAS BEEN INCREASED, WHICH ALLOWS PRESENT PROGRAMS TO BE EXPANDED AND IMPROVED. IT IS HOPED THAT INCREASES IN THE NUMBER OF SCHOLARSHIPS AND DORMITORY FACILITIES FOR PROMISING STUDENTS WILL ENCOURAGE A LARGER NUMBER OF QUALIFIED LIBERIAN STUDENTS TO ENROLL AT UL. ARRANGEMENTS ARE BEING MADE TO HAVE LIBERIAN COUNTERPARTS TO THE CU TEAM EDUCATED AND TRAINED IN THE US. THESE COUNTERPARTS WILL REPLACE THE CU TEAM MEMBERS AFTER PROJECT IS TERMINATED. MAJOR OBSTACLES STILL NEEDING IMPROVEMENT ARE: 1)DEVELOPING A SYSTEM FOR IMPROVING BUILDINGS AND GROUNDS PLANNING,MAINTENANCE,ETC; 2)ESTABLISHING OF PERSONNEL POLICIES AND PROFICIENCY RATINGS; 3)IMPROVING ADMINISTRATIVE PRACTICES AND UNIVERSITY BOARD OF TRUSTEE PERFORMANCE; 4)REDICING POLITICAL INFLUENCES IN UL DECISION MAKING,AND 5)DECREASING GO;'S SLOWNESS IN RESPONDING TO CU REQUEST.

Abstract: Project to construct two highways, one between Lahore and Multan in (West) Pakistan and the other between Dacca and Aricha in East Pakistan (Bangladesh).  Implementation responsibilities for the two highways will rest, respectively, with the Communications and Works Department, Government of West Pakistan, and the Roads and Highways Department, Government of East Pakistan (GOEP). The two-lane, hardsurface Lahore-Multan highway will extend some 207 miles; 117 miles will be improvements to existing road and 90 miles will be newly built.  A parallel ox-cart road will also be constructed.  The two-lane, all-weather Dacca-Aricha highway will extend 58 miles (construction to be funded by GOEP) and will include new ferry landings, bridges, and box culverts (to be funded by A.I.D.).

Abstract: This USAID/Thailand report, a follow-up to a 1964 Returned Participant Evaluation Survey, presents statistical data gathered from questionnaires completed by Thai participants and USAID/T technicians between April, 1964 and May, 1965.  The questionnaires covered the pre-departure, during-training, and post-training phases.  Several specific recommendations geared to Thailand but with broader applicability are made in the areas of selection, pre-departure preparation, and follow-up. (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: (Not a PES.)  Evaluates first year of project operation (5/64 - 5/65) in Thailand.  The accelerated rural development project is designed to establish, at the changwad (province) level, a capability to plan and construct rural public works projects, and to coordinate other Royal Thai Government (RTG) rural development activities in the changwad.  It is too early to evaluate goal-level achievement, i.e., increased rural income and counter-subversion.  Therefore, evaluation concentrates on the initial "tooling-up" process. The public works units established in each of 6 Northeastern changwads encountered many problems in getting established: there were no job descriptions, supervision was inadequate, and the construction season was very short due to late arrival of equipment (1/65). Emphasis has so far been on building rural roads.  The aspect of coordinating related projects of health, agriculture, water supply, and education at the changwad level is receiving little or no attention. Report recommends that the changwad public works units be expanded to include a smaller construction unit exclusively for village development projects; also suggests that the roads program be modified to include non-all-weather access roads because they can be constructed more quickly and cheaply. The Korat Engineering Center, being understaffed, was unable to provide the intended engineering and equipment backstopping to the changwads.  The Center's training activities should be delegated to established RTG institutions. The Thai chief engineers in each changwad were inadequately trained and inexperienced in engineering and construction supervision to insure sound construction practices on the number one project - roads. Governors lacked confidence in their ability and therefore tended to assume engineering responsibilities themselves.  The USOM engineering advisors are spread too thin to give adequate engineering supervision and on-the-job training to the Thai changwad engineers and their staffs. To correct this, 1 US engineering advisor should be recruited for each changwad to serve as a counterpart to the Thai Chief Engineer.

Abstract: LOAN TO GOVERNMENT OF BRAZIL (G0B) FINANCES THE PURCHASE OF EQUIPMENT AND SERVICES BOTH IN U.S. AND BRAZIL IN ORDER TO TRANSFORM THE STATE HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT OF MINAS GERAIS (DER/MG) INTO AN INSTITUTION ORGANIZED, EQUIPPED AND COMPETENT TO MAINTAIN ITS PART OF THE STATE HIGHWAY NETWORK. DER/MG'S HIGHWAY MAINTENANCE CAPABILITY COULD BECOME A LINK IN GOB'S INFRASTRUCTURE FOR DEVELOPING ITSELF ECONOMICALLY. PROJECT COMPONENTS INCLUDE: (1) PLANNING AND BUILDING A MAINTENANCE ORGANIZATION AND PROGRAM. (2) BUILDING A LOGISTICS PROGRAM. (3) DEVELOPING AN ENGINEERING PLAN. (4) INSTITUTION BUILDING WHICH WOULD INCLUDE PERMANENT IN-SERVICE TRAINING ON MAINTENANCE, MECHANICAL AND SUPERVISORY SKILLS; BUDGETING; RECORD-KEEPING; COST DISTRIBUTION BASED ON US OF ROADS AND REQUIRED EQUIPMENT/PERSONNEL AND REPLACEMENT OF SAME. (5) DER/MG SUPERVISION OF 30 STATE HIGHWAY RESIDENCIES PLANNED. DIRECT BENEFICIARIES ARE THE CONSULTING ENGINEERS, PERSONNEL BEING TRAINED, MANUFACTURERS PROVIDING EQUIPMENT/TRAINING SERVICES, AND LOCAL FIRMS. INDIRECT BENEFICIARIES ARE PERSONS INVOLVED IN AGRICULTURE, INDUSTRY AND MINING -- ALL ENTERPRISES DEPENDENT UPON EITHER TRUCK TRANSPORT OR ROADS. NEW MIDDLE LEVEL MANPOWER JOBS CREATED INCLUDE MECHANIC HELPERS, DIESEL TRUCK DRIVERS, OPERATORS OF SPECIAL ROAD EQUIPMENT. DER/MG PROPOSES TO EMPLOY A PRIVATE FIRM OF CONSULTING ENGINEERS TO OFFER ADVICE ON PERSONNEL TRAINING PROGRAM, PLAN MAINTENANCE PROGRAM, DEVELOP LOGISTICAL STRENGTHS FOR A PROPERLY FUNCTIONING ONGOING PROGRAM. FIRM WILL DEVELOP A TRAINING MANUAL FOR IN-SERVICE TRAINING. AMERICAN ASSOCIATION OF HIGHWAY OFFICIALS HAS ALREADY PROVIDED GUIDELINES FOR REPLACEMENT OF EQUIPMENT ON TIMELY BASIS AND PROPER DISTRIBUTION COSTS. AID FINANCES 100% OF FOREIGN EXCHANGE COSTS, 36% OF LOCAL COSTS. BALANCE OF LOCAL COSTS ARE CONTRIBUTED BY HOST GOVERNMENT.

Abstract: LOAN TO GOVT OF TURKEY WILL PAY COSTS OF DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION OF 380 KV TRANSMISSION LINES, SUBSTATIONS AND SWITCHYARDS NECESSARY TO CONNECT GOKCEKAYA HYDROELECTRIC PLANT WITH THE NORTHWEST ANATLOIA SYSTEM AND WILL FINANCE COST OF TRAINING TURKISH ENGINEERS IN CONSTRUCTION, OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF LINES AND EQUIPMENT. ETIBANK, A PRIVATE CORPORATION WILL CONSTRUCT A SUBSTATION WITH TEN (ONE SPARE) 35.1 MVA 14.4/380 KV SINGLE PHASE TRANSFORMERS AND SWITCHYARD AT THE GOKCEKAYA PLANT, WITH THE SUBSTATION'S TOTAL CAPACITY BEING 316 MVA; 234 MILES OF 380 KV SINGLE CIRCUIT TRANSMISSION LINE, DUAL BUNDLE 964 MCM ACSR AND STEEL TOWERS TO ANKARA AND ISTANBUL; AND TWO SUBSTATIONS AT ANKARA, EACH CONSISTING OF TWO-380/154 KV 150 MW AUTO-TRANSFORMERS AND SWITCHES AND EACH WITH A CAPACITY OF 300 MW. ELECTRICITY WILL BE TRANSMITTED THROUGH THESE FACILITIES TO THE 154 KV GRID AT ISTANBUL AND ANKARA. THE GOKCEKAYA 380 KV PLANT SUBSTATION AND SWITCHYARD WILL REPLACE THE 154 KV SUBSTATION CONSTRUCTED UNDER AN EARLIER LOAN PROJECT. THESE FUNDS AND THOSE FOR THE 154 KV TRANSMISSION FACILITES IN THE PRIOR LOAN WILL BE USED TO PARTIALLY MEET THE CONSTRUCTION COSTS OF THE GOKCEKAYA 380 KV PLANT SUBSTATION AND SWITHYARD. ETIBANK WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR CONSTRUCTION WITH ASSISTANCE FROM US ENGINEERING CONSULTANTS IN TRAINING TURKISH ENGINEERS IN US. THE PROJECT WILL IMPROVE ELECTRICAL SERVICE AND WILL INDIRECTLY ASSIST EXISTING AND FUTUREINDUSTRIES WHICH NEED RELIABLE ELECTRICITY.

Abstract: Evaluates the Contractor's Report (U-510) submitted by the University of California (UCLA) for the period 11/63 - 11/64 in Nigeria. UCLA provides technical assistance in the establishment of the Port Harcourt Comprehensive Secondary School.  The report reflects on problem areas to the virtual exclusion of detailed accomplishments in cirriculum development.  It contains little of the specific planning that has been done to prepare for the projected Port Harcourt Comprehensive Secondary School. Problem areas include provision of adequate maintenance for school facilities, delayed classroom construction, staff housing, and maintaining staff stability. Student and faculty morale dropped during this period, culminating in a student strike in protest against lack of information. Steps taken by UCLA, the Ministry of Education, and USAID to correct this have brought substantial improvements.

Abstract: Evaluates performance of the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA), for the period 9/64 - 3/65 in Nigeria.  UCLA is on contract to assist the Nigerian Ministry of Education in establishing the Port Harcourt Comprehensive Secondary School. The project has been confronted with difficult problems during the rating period, the most serious being the student strike of 10/64.  The strike was precipitated by student unrest over lack of communication within the School regarding the administration of the West African School Certificate for fifth form students.  The strike severely deteriorated relations between the School administration and the Ministry. Aside from this problem, USAID is concerned that UCLA has not "tooled-up" sufficiently to carry out a project of this magnitude. Campus backstopping is insufficient.  Curriculum development has been left almost entirely to the field party, most of whom have been unable to devote adequate time to this vital area.  The UCLA campus staff should be providing curriculum workshops, short-term consultants, and curriculum review. USAID's concern is clearly justified since this type of secondary school is completely foreign to traditional Nigerian educational practice.  This school is multipurpose, large, and coeducational; Nigerian schools are not. Nigerian schools are of five years duration; this one, six.  Thus, the building of this new institution strikes at very wide and firmly held traditional beliefs.  Development of an imaginative, realistic curriculum is essential, especially if the school is to serve as a model for future projects. It now appears that the UCLA campus does have adequate personnel to provide sufficient backstopping, and USAID is looking for a much firmer grasp of the project and a much greater involvement by the Unversity in the project development. Most contract team members are highly competent and well fitted for their assignments. Participant training remains a major strength of the project. USAID anticipates that all key areas will be staffed in part by returned participants when the school goes into its expansion.

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDED TO COMPANHIA PARANAENSE DE ENERGIA ELECTRICA (COPEL), THE ELECTRICAL UTILITY OF THE BRAZILIAN STATE OF PARANA, TO EXPAND AND IMPROVE ELECTRICAL GENERATING AND TRANSMISSION SYSTEMS IN THAT STATE. PROJECT COMPONENTS INCLUDE: 1) THE EXPANSION AND IMPROVEMENTS TO THE EXISTING GENERATION AND TRANSMISSION SYSTEM IN THE NORTHERN AND EASTERN REGIONS OF PARANA (THE "MAIN SYSTEM") THROUGH THE CONSTRUCTION OF TRANSMISSION LINES AND ASSOCIATED SUBSTATIONS AND SWITCHING STATIONS, AND THE INSTALLATION OF 5 PACKAGE-TYPE DIESEL ELECTRIC GENERATING UNITS (TOTALLING 15,000 KW) TO MEET INTERIM POWER NEEDS; 2) EXPANSION AND IMPROVEMENTS TO THE GENERATION AND TRANSMISSION SYSTEMS OF 5 OF THE 6 ISOLATED SYSTEMS IN WESTERN PARANA THROUGH THE INSTALLATION OF 5 PACKAGE-TYPE GENERATING UNITS AND THE CONSTRUCTION OF TRANSMISSION LINES AND ASSOCIATED SUBSTATIONS. (AS HYDROELECTRIC POWER BECOMES AVAILABLE IN THE EASTERN PART OF THE STATE, FROM PLANTS NOW UNDER CONSTRUCTION, THE PACKAGED-TYPE DIESEL GENERATOR UNITS INITIALLY INSTALLED  IN THE MAIN SYSTEM WILL BE TRANFERRED TO THE ISOLATED SYSTEMS, GIVING THESE SYSTEMS 10 AID-FINANCED UNITS.); AND 3) THE ESTABLISHMENT OF A TRAINING PROGRAM IN UTILITY OPERATIONS AND MAINTENANCE, AND THE INITIATION OF IMPROVED UTILITY COST CONTROL AND ACCOUNTING PROCEDURES. LOAN WILL FINANCE THE 30,000 KW'S OF PACKAGED DIESELS, 220 KV AND 66 KV TRANSMISSION LINES, SUBSTATIONS, AND CONSULTING ENGINEERING AND PROFESSIONAL SERVICES. COPEL WILL PROVIDE ALL LOCAL COSTS. PROJECT IS PART OF COPEL'S OVERALL PROGRAM TO REPLACE MOST OF THE EXISTING SMALL AND INEFFICIENT POWER PLANTS WITH MORE ECONOMIC HYDRO PLANTS; INTERCONNECT THE VARIOUS SYSTEMS INTO ONE LARGE "MAIN SYSTEM", AND TO EXPAND 6 SMALLER ISOLATED SYSTEMS WHICH WILL BE INTERCONNECTED AT SOME FUTURE DATE.

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDED TO THE COMPANHIA HIDROELECTRICA DE BOA ESPERANCA (COHEBE) FOR A HYDROELECTRIC PLANT AT BOA ESPERANCA IN NORTHEAST BRAZIL AND A TRANSMISSION SYSTEM FOR THE PLANT SERVING THE NORTHERN SECTION OF THE STATES OF PIAUI AND MARANHAO. THE LOAN WILL ASSIST IN FINANCING THE FOREIGN EXCHANGE ANDLOCAL COSTS OF (A) ENGINEERING SERVICES, (B) GOODS AND RELATED SERVICES FOR THE POWER HOUSE AND TRANSMISSION SYSTEM, (C) MAINTENANCE EQUIPMENT PROCURED BY COHEBE, AND (D) TRAINING IN THE US AND PUERTO RICO FOR COHEBE PERSONNEL. GOB WILL FINANCE 81.5% OF PROJECT COSTS INCLUDING ALL CONSTRUCTION SERVICES. THE INITIAL PLANT WILL HAVE A CAPACITY OF 108 MV WHICH CAN BE EXPANDED WITH ADDITIONAL GENERATING UNITS. THE ULTIMATE FIRM CAPACITY OF THE GENERATING PLANT IN A NORMAL WATER YEAR WILL BE 155 MW AND 745 MILLION KWH PER YEAR. THE DAM, WHICH HAS BEEN UNDER CONSTRUCTION SINCE 8/64, WILL BE OF A ROCK FILL TYPE WITH AN IMPERVIOUS EARTH CORE, 5,850 METERS LONG AND WITH A MAXIMUM HEIGHT OF 53 METERS. THE PROJECT INCLUDES THE DAM, TWO SPILLWAYS, INTAKE, PENSTOCKS, POWER HOUSE, TAILRACE, STEP-UP SUBSTATION, AND AN INITIAL 600 MILE, 230 KV AND 69 KV TRANSMISSION SYSTEM WITH STEP-DOWN SUBSTATIONS AT LOAD CENTERS. DAM WILL ALSO BE USED FOR FLOOD CONTROL AND POSSIBLY IRRIGATION.

Abstract: A TOTAL OF 602 KM OF ALL-WEATHER ACCESS ROADS WILL BE CONSTRUCTED IN RURAL HONDURAS. THESE ROADS ARE EXPECTED TO LOWER THE TRANSPORTATION COSTS TO THE FARMER FOR HIS GOODS, AND PROVIDE GREATER ACCESSABILITY TO NEW IDEAS. BOTH RESULTS SHOULD STIMULATE PRODUCTION, INCREASE FARM REVENUE, AND INCREASE FOOD SUPPLY. ADDITIONALLY, NEW PEOPLE WILL HAVE TO BE HIRED BY THE HIGHWAY DIVISION OF THE MINISTRY OF COMMUNICATIONS AND PUBLIC WORKS TO MAINTAIN AND SERVICE THESE ROADS. PRINCIPAL LOCATIONS FOR ROADS WILL BE: AGUAN VALLEY, CHOLUTECA AREA AND TEGUCIGALPA-CATACANAS ROUTE. THESE ARE ALL POPULATED AREAS NOW REACHED ONLY BY PACK ANIMAL OR ON FOOT. THIS PROJECT REDUCES TO 20% THOSE HONDURANS WITHOUT ADEQUATE ROAD ACCESS.

Abstract: 3/64-3/65. 9 UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN SPECIALISTS AT WORK IN PORTO ALEGRE AND ONE IN RIO DE JANERO. 23 STUDENTS IN AGRICULTURAL ECONOMICS, SOILS, FORAGE CROPS, AND ANIMAL NUTRITION HAVE COMPLETED THE FIRST SEMESTER OF GRADUATE WORK UNDER THESE SPECIALISTS. SUCCESSFUL POST-GRADUATE COURSE FOR VETERINARY STUDENTS COMPLETED IN JULY, RESULTING IN PLANS FOR DEVELOPMENT OF PERMANENT GRADUATE COURSE IN VETERINARY MEDICINE. FIELD WORK FINISHED IN STUDIES OF EDUCATIONAL ATTITUDES OF RURAL PEOPLE, COMMUNICATIONS PROBLEMS OF AGRICULTURAL TECHNICIANS, AND PRODUCTION MEASUREMENTS OF LARGE CATTLE RANCHES. ADDITIONALLY, WORK ON FERTILIZER RESPONSE IN RICE, SORGHUM, AND WINTER PASTURES HAS BEEN COMPLETED. BRAZILIAN AND AMERICAN PROFESSORS HAVE COLLABORATED IN PREPARING LONG RANGE DEVELOPMENT PLANS FOR THE UNIVERSITY; INCREASED UNIVERSITY RUDGETARY SUPPORT OF CONTRACTOR ACTIVITIES PROMISED BY UNIVERSITY.

Abstract: 3/65-7/65. UNIVERSITY OF ARIZONA STAFF, WORKING WITH UNIVERSITY OF CEARA FACULTY, HAVE EXPANDED CURRICULUM AND INTENSIFIED RESEARCH ACTIVITIES. BRAZILIAN FACULTY ARE PREPARING FOR ADVANCED TRAINING IN RELEVENT AREAS IN UNITED STATED. SEMINARS HAVE BEEN ORGANIZED TO STIMULATE CLOSER WORKING RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN BRAZILIAN AND US FACULTY MEMBERS. EXPANSION OF RESEARCH AND EXTENSION ACTIVITIES PLANNED. PROBLEM AREAS ARE THE LACK OF CRUZEIRO GRANTS AND TENDENCY OF MANY YOUNG PROFESSORS TO SEEK LUCRATIVE EMPLOYMENT IN NON-ACADEMIC FIELDS.

Abstract: This report attempts to evaluate the most significant aspects of the animal-health, livestock-development, range-management, 1ivestock marketing, and educational-development programs in the West African region.  Several diseases, principally rinderpest, trypanosomiasis, and contagious bovine pleuropneumonia (CBPP) are of immediate concern to these programs.  However, a number of other diseases and parasitic conditions existing in this and other regions of Africa also impede the development of a sound livestock industry.  Foot-and-mouth disease, for instance, certainly equals rinderpest as a cause for the restricted trade in livestock products, and widespread parasitism results in huge, inadequately measured and documented losses.  (Author abstract)

Abstract: During World War II, and in the years since the end of that global and massive conflict, the United States has conducted economic and military assistance programs, recognizing that her own security depends in large measure on the strength of other free nations.  These assistance programs, to a considerable degree, have become matters of necessity rather than matters of choice, because the United States is faced with awesome uncertainties in a dangerous and turbulent world. What follows, then, is a collection of basic data on the American foreign assistance program since the adoption of the Lend-Lease Program on 11 March 1941.  This basic data is just that; it does not comprise an journal article in the usual sense of the word.  Presented here in summary form, though, the data should prove a useful reference tool. (Author abstract, modified)
